    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Let me explain. In the first case:\n\n```\ndf['B'][:4] = range(4)\n```\n\nyou are assigning values into the first 4 locations of the Series returned by `df['B']`. In the second case:\n\n```\ndf[:4]['B'] = range(4)\n```\n\nyou are assigning the _entire B column_ of the DataFrame slice `df[:4]` to be the list `[0, 1, 2, 3]`. Because it's an entire column assignment, DataFrame is intended to allow column types to change. You can prove it to yourself:\n\n```\n\nIn [4]: df\nOut[4]: \n          A         B         C\n0 -1.191583  1.290778 -0.445384\n1 -1.275654 -0.716870  1.068261\n2 -0.179524 -1.783951  2.539275\n3 -0.149163  0.621901 -0.326219\n4  0.055287 -0.057617  1.015610\n5 -0.816133 -0.505380 -0.480527\n6  0.531102  0.292489  0.362619\n7 -0.467907  0.179168 -0.892605\n\nIn [5]: chunk = df[:4]\n\nIn [6]: df.dtypes\nOut[6]: \nA    float64\nB    float64\nC    float64\n\nIn [7]: chunk.dtypes\nOut[7]: \nA    float64\nB    float64\nC    float64\n\nIn [8]: chunk['B'] = range(4)\n\nIn [9]: chunk.dtypes\nOut[9]: \nA    float64\nB      int64\nC    float64\n\nIn [10]: df.dtypes\nOut[10]: \nA    float64\nB    float64\nC    float64\n```\n\nThe question is: if the values you're setting can be coerced to the current type, perhaps that obeys POLS. I will think about it. \n"
  },
